{
    "analysis": "The component-level aggregation shows widespread anomalies concentrated on OS nodes: 43 components had anomalies and many os_* nodes (os_006, os_010, os_001, os_002, os_021, ...) have 100% of their scanned KPIs anomalous within the incident window, with earliest anomalies at the exact start of the window (1590768000 => 2020-05-30 00:00:00 CST). os_021 stands out with a very large max_breach_ratio (93.0) and several OS nodes show large breach ratios as well. This indicates a strong node-level signal starting at the start of the window rather than a late downstream service fault. However, multiple nodes are affected which conflicts with the report of a \"single failure\" — we must use traces to disambiguate whether a single component (e.g., a specific OS node or container) is the root cause or whether this is a systemic/propagated issue. Next step: perform trace-level anomaly scanning (compute global thresholds for each trace series using the full trace.csv, then detect in-window breaches) to find which trace series (and which components in traces) show earliest and most severe anomalies and whether traces point to a single downstream faulty component (e.g., a docker or a specific os_021/os_022).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "On trace.csv perform a compact anomaly scan: 1) Restrict trace series to cmdb_ids in the allowed root-cause sets (os_001..os_022, docker_001..docker_008, db_001..db_013). 2) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 across the full available trace.csv (do NOT compute P95 using filtered window). 3) Filter trace.csv to the incident window timestamps >=1590768000 and <=1590769800. 4) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in-window, count window_count and anomaly_count where value >= global_P95; also capture earliest_anomaly_timestamp_raw (min timestamp where anomaly occurred), earliest_anomaly_local (local time string), and max_anomaly_value in-window. 5) Return a compact JSON table limited to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, window_count, anomaly_count, anomaly_percent, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_raw, earliest_anomaly_local, max_anomaly_value. Also return two scalars: total_trace_series_scanned and total_trace_anomaly_count_sum. Keep outputs compact and JSON-serializable; do not return full time series." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace scan found many trace series flagged because their global P95 == 0 and we used value >= P95, which makes zero-valued series appear anomalous. Metric-level aggregation earlier showed a strong node-level signal: 43 components had anomalies, and many os_* nodes (os_006, os_010, os_001, os_002, os_021, ...) each had 100% of their scanned KPIs anomalous starting exactly at the incident window start (1590768000 => 2020-05-30 00:00:00 CST). os_006 has the largest total anomaly points, os_021 and os_004 show very high breach ratios for at least one KPI. This indicates a node-level incident beginning at 00:00 rather than a single downstream service fault; however, multiple OS nodes are affected which conflicts with the report of a \"single failure.\" To localize the single root cause we must (1) inspect per-KPI anomaly characteristics for the top candidate nodes to identify the most severe resource deviation and map it to a root cause reason (CPU, network, DB, etc.), and (2) refine trace anomalies to ignore zero-threshold artifacts so traces can confirm whether a single container/service is the downstream faulty component. I will first request a focused metric deep-dive on the top OS candidates to identify which resource KPI shows the largest and most meaningful breach (severity, earliest time).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the metric KPI summary table (or recompute it if needed), examine per-KPI anomaly details for these top 5 candidate components: os_006, os_010, os_001, os_002, os_021. For each of these components, return a compact list (limit to top 20 rows per component) of KPIs that had anomaly_count > 0 in the incident window, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, window_count, anomaly_count, anomaly_percent (anomaly_count/window_count), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_raw, earliest_anomaly_local, max_anomaly_value, breach_ratio (as previously computed: max_anomaly_value/global_p95, or max_anomaly_value if global_p95==0). Sort each component's list by breach_ratio descending then anomaly_count descending. Also return a small summary per component: total_kpis_scanned, num_kpis_with_anomalies, total_anomaly_points, earliest_anomaly_local_overall. Keep outputs JSON-serializable, compact, and limit rows returned (max 20 per component). Do NOT return full raw time series." }

{
    "analysis": "The referenced-component aggregation found 10 referenced components with trace anomalies (443 trace anomaly points). Top references are mostly docker containers (docker_002/003/004/001 etc.) and two OS nodes (os_021, os_022). Many of these referenced components also have metric anomalies (metric_anomaly_flag=True). Earliest trace anomalies for some components (docker_002, os_022, docker_008, docker_005) occur at the exact window start (1590768000 => 2020-05-30 00:00:00 CST). Metric analysis showed severe disk/I/O/iowait spikes on certain OS nodes (notably os_001, os_002, os_021) with very high breach ratios for disk-related KPIs. We need to determine a single root cause component (single failure) by combining trace call-chain direction and timing with metric severity. The next concrete step is to inspect the trace series that contributed anomalies for the top referenced candidate (docker_002) to see: which specific trace series flagged, their earliest anomaly times, whether they indicate traffic coming from or going to other components (e.g., 'from_os_022' or 'to_docker_008'), and whether docker_002 is the downstream endpoint in those traces. This will help decide if docker_002 is the downstream faulty component (container-level) or whether the root cause is instead an OS node (e.g., os_021/os_022) driving the container symptoms.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For referenced_component == 'docker_002' produce a compact JSON table (limit 20 rows) listing the distinct trace series that contributed anomalies in the strict nonzero-P95 trace anomaly set. For each contributing series (one row per unique (cmdb_id, trace_name)) return: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, window_count (in-window rows), anomaly_count (in-window rows where value > global_p95), anomaly_percent, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_raw (min timestamp where value > global_p95), earliest_anomaly_local (local time string), max_anomaly_value (in-window), and referenced_components (list of component tokens parsed from trace_name matching 'os_\\d{3}','docker_\\d{3}','db_\\d{3}'). Sort rows by earliest_anomaly_timestamp_raw ascending then anomaly_count descending. Also return two scalars: total_series_for_docker_002 (count of distinct series) and total_anomaly_points_for_docker_002 (sum of anomaly_count). Keep outputs JSON-serializable and bounded (<=20 rows). If 'docker_002' has no contributing anomaly series, return an empty list and a short error_message explaining that." }

